{"cursor":"5972","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Bruno Bianchi' (c. 1955 â December 2, 2011) was a French cartoonist and\nanimator. Bianchi worked extensively as an artist, film and television director\nand screenwriter for animated productions, including the series [[Inspector\nGadget]], [[Rainbow Brite]], [[Heathcliff (1984 TV series)|Heathcliff]] and its\nspinoff film, [[Heathcliff: The Movie]] in 1986.\n\nIn 1980, Bianchi directed two series for DiC Audiovisuel, the studio he had been\nworking for since 1977. One of them was Cro et Bronto (Cro and Bronto), a series\nof 45 episodes Ã¡ 1 minute and 20 seconds each, about a stone age man trying to\ncatch and eat a brontosaurus. The other series, Archibald le Magichien\n(Archibald the Magic Dog), was an educational show, running for 46 episodes,\nabout a magic anthropomorphic dog (in reality an old wizard who had lost the\nmagic formula allowing him to become himself again). Archibald befriends a young\nboy named Pierre and go on many highbrow adventures with him, teaching him\nimportant lifestyle lessons along the way. This series was presumably the first\nmajor collaboration between Bianchi and Jean Chalopin, who, as the founder and\nCEO of DiC, developed the show. Both Cro et Bronto and Archibald le Magichien\nare very hard to find today.\n\nIn 1981-82, Bianchi co-created the animated television series [[Inspector\nGadget]] together with Andy Heyward and DiC's founder Jean Chalopin. Bianchi also served as main character designer and supervising\ndirector on the show, which ran for two seasons and became one of the most\niconic series created by DiC.\n\nBianchi worked as a producer, artist, animator, television and film director,\nand writer for numerous other DiC Entertainment, Saban Entertainment and S.I.P.\nAnimation productions from the 1980s until the early 2000s. His credits include\n[[Heathcliff (1984 TV series)|Heathcliff]], [[Jayce and the Wheeled Warriors]],\n[[M.A.S.K. (TV series)|M.A.S.K.]], [[Rainbow Brite]], [[Iznogoud]], [[W.I.T.C.H.\n(TV series)|W.I.T.C.H.]], [[Diplodos]], [[Beverly Hills Teens]], [[Princess\nSissi (1997 TV series)|Princess Sissi]] and [[Gadget and the Gadgetinis]] (a\nspinoff of Inspector Gadget).\n\nIn 2008, Bianchi founded his own studio, named Ginkgo Animation, following the\nclosure of S.I.P. International.\n\nBiachi died on December 2, 2011, at the age of 56. He was\nburied in PÃ¨re Lachaise Cemetery in Paris on December 6, 2011.\n","linknr":184,"url":"Bruno_Bianchi_(cartoonist)","recorded":1375070558,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Bruno_Bianchi_(cartoonist)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Bruno_Bianchi_(cartoonist)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/France","/wiki/Cartoonist","/wiki/Animator","/wiki/Television_director","/wiki/Screenwriter","/wiki/Inspector_Gadget","/wiki/Rainbow_Brite","/wiki/Heathcliff_(1984_TV_series)","/wiki/Heathcliff:_The_Movie","#cite_note-cartoonbrew-1","#cite_note-animag-2","/wiki/DiC_Audiovisuel","/w/index.php?title=Cro_et_Bronto&action=edit&redlink=1","/w/index.php?title=Cro_and_Bronto&action=edit&redlink=1","/w/index.php?title=Archibald_le_Magichien&action=edit&redlink=1","/w/index.php?title=Archibald_the_Magic